Synthetic Data¶

Purpose: This notebook is a proof-of-concept to get familiar with generating synthetic data. I used the references below to get acquainted with the process and to try it on a different dataset.¶

I used the Synthetic Data Vault (SDV), which is a Python library designed to be a one-stop shop for creating tabular synthetic data. The SDV offers multiple machine learning models -- ranging from classical statistical methods (Copulas) to deep learning methods (GANs). It can generate data for single tables, multiple connected tables or sequential tables.
In this notebook, I used a Copulas synthesizer.

Why do we need Synthetic data?¶

  • Privacy and Compliance: Real-world datasets often contain sensitive information. Synthetic data, however, does not carry the same privacy concerns since it's generated and doesn't correspond to real individuals.

  • Data Imbalance: Synthetic data can help alleviate problems with imbalanced datasets, where one class of data is over-represented compared to another. This is a common issue in machine learning and can lead to biased or incorrect models. Synthetic data can be generated to balance the dataset, improving the performance of the machine learning model.

  • Data Augmentation: Synthetic data can augment existing datasets, particularly when real-world data is scarce or expensive to obtain. For instance, in fields like autonomous driving or healthcare, acquiring enough real-world data can be challenging and costly. Synthetic data can fill in the gaps, providing more comprehensive datasets for training models.

  • Experimentation and Robustness: Synthetic data allows for more controlled experimentation because you can generate data under various conditions that may not be present in your real-world data but could be encountered in the future. This can lead to models that are more robust and generalize better.

  • Reduced Time and Cost: Collecting and labeling real-world data can be time-consuming and expensive. Synthetic data generation can be automated, potentially saving time and resources.

  • Data Understanding: By generating synthetic data, analysts and machine learning practitioners can better understand the structure and properties of the data, which can be valuable in feature engineering and model selection.

  • Simulating Rare Events: Synthetic data can be used to simulate rare events that don't occur frequently in the collected real-world data, but are important to model accurately, such as fraudulent transactions in credit card data or certain types of network intrusions in cybersecurity.

Jet Engine - Load & Prepare Data¶

Note, this dataset is sequential in nature.

There are specific synthetic data models that can be used for such data, but I chose to start with a simple model first.

In [ ]:
# read training data 
train_raw_df = pd.read_csv('./data/train_FD001.txt', sep=" ", header=None)

# remove two columns that have NaN
# Drop columns 26 and 27
train_raw_df = train_raw_df.drop(columns=[26, 27])

# name the cols
train_raw_df.columns = ['id', 'cycle', 'setting1', 'setting2', 'setting3', 's1', 's2', 's3',
                     's4', 's5', 's6', 's7', 's8', 's9', 's10', 's11', 's12', 's13', 's14',
                     's15', 's16', 's17', 's18', 's19', 's20', 's21']

# create separate df with the unit id and the max cycle
rul = pd.DataFrame(train_raw_df.groupby('id')['cycle'].max()).reset_index()
rul.columns = ['id', 'max']

# join the two datasets on the unit id
train_df = train_raw_df.merge(rul, on=['id'], how='left')

# subtract cycle from the max cycles to get RUL
train_df['RUL'] = train_df['max'] - train_df['cycle']
train_df = train_df.drop(columns=[('max')])

# create traget var
cycle_cutoff = 30
train_df['fail_in_30_label'] = np.where(train_df['RUL'] <= cycle_cutoff, 1, 0 )
train_df.head()

# Note: in a previous notebook, I did extensive Exploratory Data Analysis on this dataset:

# The sensors in the list -except 13,14 - are constant or nearly so, so no need for producing synthetic data.  
# s13 & 14 were not constant, but, interestingly, the synthesizer GENERATED synthetic data that was a constant
# So, I'm also removing s13 & 14 from this proof-of-concept in order for the quality report to work correctly.  (it will churn, producing warnings if synthetic data is constant)

remove_cols = ['setting3', 's1','s5','s6','s10','s16','s18','s19','s13','s14']
valid_cols =  [x for x in train_df.columns if x not in remove_cols]
train_df_valid = train_df[valid_cols]

Synthesize Data¶

We will be using the Gaussian Copula Synthesizer which uses classical statistical methods to train a model and generate synthetic data.
https://docs.sdv.dev/sdv/single-table-data/modeling/synthesizers/gaussiancopulasynthesizer

https://docs.sdv.dev/sdv/single-table-data/data-preparation/single-table-metadata-api

Step 4: Evaluation¶

The synthetic data replicates the mathematical properties of the real data. The evaluations below compare the real and synthetic data to determine whether the statistical and mathematical properties are similar.

  • https://docs.sdv.dev/sdv/single-table-data/evaluation
  • https://colab.research.google.com/drive/19Bz3os18x9GTS30n4d_Tw2frUVYG1KJn?usp=sharing#scrollTo=X-qWBINLpvn8

Overall Quality

# this ran for 6min
# Note: if some of the synthetic data is constant, this report will spin, never erroring, just giving warnings and never complete. 
quality_report = evaluate_quality(
    real_data=train_df_valid,
    synthetic_data=synthetic_data,
    metadata=metadata)

Column Shapes

  • This property looks at the overall shape the columns to see if the synthetic data matches the real data. The report details indicate which columns have a better scores for this property. It also indicates which metric was used to compute the quality score (based on the data type).
  • Sensor #9 had the lowest quality. From my experience using this dataset, this sensor did not have a clear data pattern so I'm not surprised by this.

Diagnostics
Diagnostics check to see if the synthetic rows are pure copies of the real data, if the synthetic data covers the full range of values and if the synthetic data adheres to the original ranges.
https://docs.sdv.dev/sdv/single-table-data/evaluation
